<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
When the work has seven or more authors, cite only the name of the first author followed by et al. 
and the date. (Note the full stop after et al.).  
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Davis et al. (2003) found that&hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: A recent study (Davis et al. 2003) found that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
When the work is referred to more than once in the same paragraph do not include the date in 
subsequent references, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited. 
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	In a recent study, Davis et al. (2003) showed that&hellip; Davis et al. also found that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
If you directly quote fewer than 30 words, enclose the quotation using single quotation marks and
include the page number(s).
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Davis et al. (2003, p. 21) observe that &#8216;we have an irreversible dependency upon digital 
	technology&#8217;. 
	<br>
	Alternatively: Subsequently, &#8216;we have an irreversible dependency upon digital 
	technology&#8217; (Davis et al. 2003, p. 21).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 30 words it should be displayed in a double&#45;spaced, indented block
(1.3cm) without quotation marks.
